  "business_context": "Lead records are pre-Contact, pre-Account holding cells for prospects who have signaled interest but haven't been qualified yet — a webform fill, a tradeshow scan, a list-purchased name, a cold-outreach response. The Lead-vs-Contact split is one of the most architecturally divergent decisions in CRM modeling. Three patterns exist: (1) explicit Lead entity with conversion (Salesforce, EspoCRM, NPSP) — Lead has its own table, lifecycle, and a one-way conversion process that creates Account+Contact+Opportunity records when the Lead qualifies; (2) unified Contact with status (HubSpot) — no separate Lead table; the pre-qualification state is just `lifecyclestage=lead` on the Contact; (3) no lead concept at all (Attio, CiviCRM, Bloomerang) — every person is a Contact / Person / Constituent from day one, with no pre-qualification entity. The choice has significant operational consequences: separate-Lead deployments suffer from \"lead vs contact\" duplicate confusion, conversion-loss data complexity, and reporting complexity that spans both objects; unified-Contact deployments avoid these but lose the disposable, qualification-gating semantics that some sales teams want. When interviewing clients, surface \"Lead\" by asking whether they need a separate workflow for unqualified prospects that's distinct from how they handle confirmed contacts: do unqualified prospects need to be handled by a different team (SDR) than qualified ones (AE)? do they want a clean separation between \"real\" relationships and inbound-list noise? if yes, they need a backend that supports a Lead entity natively. Nonprofit deployments rarely use Leads since donors and volunteers are typically Contacts from initial entry.",
  "catalog_id": "lead",
